    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-12-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-12-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="491"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d491">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.2231/96</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Ecuador</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sparks</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 652</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Quito</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-12-30">December 30,
                            1936</date>.<lb/>[Received January 8, 1937.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to refer to the Department’s
                    telegram No. 44 of December 24, 3 p.m., 1936,<note n="15" xml:id="d491fn15">
                        <ref target="frus1936v05#pg_516">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid</hi>., p. 516</ref>.</note> directing that I
                    inform the authorities that the American Government is now prepared to initiate
                    negotiations with a view to the conclusion of a beneficial trade agreement, and
                    that I obtain their acquiescence to the proposed announcement of intention to
                    negotiate as outlined in paragraph one of the said telegram.</p>
                <p>In compliance with this instruction I explained to the Minister for Foreign
                    Affairs on the afternoon of December 28th our procedure in the premises and I
                    delivered to him my note No. 143, a copy of which is enclosed herewith.<note
                        n="16" xml:id="d491fn16">Not printed.</note> He stated that he perceived no
                    objection to the procedure outlined, but that he desired to consult with the
                    Minister of Finance before committing his Government.</p>
                <p>On Tuesday evening the Under Secretary for Foreign Affairs informed me orally
                    that the proposed public announcement was agreeable to Ecuador and that I would
                    receive a note on the following day confirming his assurance. Accordingly, I
                    sent my telegram No. 63, December 29th, 7 p.m., 1936,<note n="17"
                        xml:id="d491fn17">
                        <ref target="frus1936v05#pg_517">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1936, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">v</hi>, p. 517</ref>.</note> reporting these
                    assurances so that the <pb facs="0492" n="482" xml:id="pg_482"/> Department
                    might have sufficient time to prepare the announcement for publication on
                    January 2, 1937.</p>
                <p>This afternoon I received note No. 151 from the Foreign Minister and I enclose
                    herewith a copy with English translation.<note n="18" xml:id="d491fn18">Not
                        printed.</note> It will be observed that formal assent is given to the
                    proposed public announcement<note n="19" xml:id="d491fn19">Department of State,
                            <hi rend="italic">Press Releases</hi>, January 9, 1937, p. 16.</note>
                    outlined by the Department.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Edward J. Sparks</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
